content:
Creating a program that generates a unique encryption key for each user and decrypts their data only with the correct key involves implementing cryptographic techniques. An analogy for this system in HTML format can be designed as follows:

### HTML Analogy

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Encryption Key Analogy</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        .container {
            border: 2px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 10px;
            padding: 20px;
            max-width: 500px;
        }
        .door {
            margin: 10px 0;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
        }
        .door.locked {
            background-color: #f44336; /* Red for locked */
        }
        .door.unlocked {
            background-color: #4CAF50; /* Green for unlocked */
        }
        .key {
            margin-top: 10px;
            padding: 5px 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            border-radius: 5px;
            background-color: #e0e0e0;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="container">
    <h2>Encryption Key System</h2>
    <div class="door locked" id="door">
        <p><strong>Door Status:</strong> Locked</p>
    </div>
    <div>
        <label for="keyInput">Enter Key:</label>
        <input type="text" id="keyInput" placeholder="Enter your unique key">
        <button onclick="unlockDoor()">Unlock</button>
    </div>
    <div class="key" id="userKey">
        <p><strong>Your Unique Key:</strong> <span id="keyDisplay"></span></p>
    </div>
</div>

<script>
    const userKey = generateUniqueKey();
    document.getElementById("keyDisplay").innerText = userKey;

    function generateUniqueKey() {
        // Simple key generation for analogy purposes
        return Math.random().toString(36).substring(2, 15);
    }

    function unlockDoor() {
        const inputKey = document.getElementById("keyInput").value;
        const doorElement = document.getElementById("door");

        if (inputKey === userKey) {
            doorElement.classList.remove("locked");
            doorElement.classList.add("unlocked");
            doorElement.innerHTML = "<p><strong>Door Status:</strong> Unlocked</p>";
        } else {
            alert("Incorrect Key! Please try again.");
        }
    }
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation

- **Door Analogy**: The locked door represents encrypted data. It can only be accessed (unlocked) with the correct key.

- **Unique Key**: Each user has a unique key generated using a simple random string method (`Math.random().toString(36).substring(2, 15)`). This key acts as the encryption key.

- **Unlocking the Door**: When the user inputs the key, the script checks if it matches the unique key. If it does, the door's status changes to "Unlocked," representing decrypted data access.

This HTML analogy provides a visual and interactive representation of how encryption keys work to secure data and how data is accessible only with the correct key.
